I didn’t want to embarrass the kid with some long flowery post but I didn’t want the day to slip by with anything too mundane and ordinary.

That’s not him.

Elaiwe is the kind of kid you love instantly. He is the brightest and most consistent smile. He wears kindness like an honor bestowed upon him. He’s got jokes— real ones—not the ones that encourage soft, childish giggles but rather full throated, belly filled laughter.  He will sit you down and tell you about Rick & Morty and Gumball and start laughing before he gets to his own punchline. Or he’ll grab the remote and make you watch the greatest goals of all time with the same level of commitment and intensity. 

He’s the standout in many rooms, and on many fields, but he is determined to make sure the people around him know they shine too. I included his soccer stats because it’s a true reflection of who he is: 

11 goals AND 11 assists. 

The kid is a helper. He’s a life saver. He’s a light. He’s a joy. He would be my favorite even if he was just a kid down the street. I love him as a mother should but I genuinely like him as a person.

He’s truly one of the best people this world has to offer. 

Happy 16th Birthday E Boogie Baby Boy (almost man)

PS. Last year, on his birthday, you all came together and gave him the gift of football. Because of you, he will be training in Barcelona this spring. This year,  we would like to gift his teammates the same opportunity. I will be posting the link soon. 
Thanks 

(See @elaiwe.ikpi_ I kept it short and unembarassing. Love you, babe)

It’s the way she falls deeper and deeper in love with herself every day. 
Never felt this strong, this confident, this content, this stable, this optimistic, this beautiful— all at once— in her life.

Prepare to be sick of her in 2023.

The last few years have been challenging for most of us. At some point in 2022, I decided to try a little bit harder to get out of the “almost” and nudge my life a few inches. 

I wondered what would happen if I freed myself a little bit; learned how to love the way this body has carried me through. 

Thought of all the times I cursed it, refused to feed it, refused to exist with it, and not in complete defiance.  I hated the times I was hospitalized because the body wasn't making enough blood-- the one thing it was meant to do, and it was failing. I refused to love it. 

But what if I tried? 

So I did and slowly it began to love me back. 

The body is older. The child left marks, but he's 16 now, and how long will I mourn the body that was never appreciated? I would have left, too, if I had been so neglected and taken for granted. 

And I learned to do that too-- leave when I felt neglected and taken for granted. 

But ultimately what I’ve learned is that age is not a curse. It is an honor.

And I will honor it. 

What I’m trying to say is that I’m fine as fuck again. 
Prepare to be sick of me. 

Respectfully. 

Happy New Year!

I was doing everything in my power to return this  @fumithelabel dress. I didn’t think I could pull it off because “I don’t do body con. It’s not for me.” I was wearing customer service out (sorry, y’all) trying to get them to accept the return. 
The little sister  @kankaleen convinced me to keep it. I’m glad I listened because who knew your girl was so hungry— until she ate?  This dress is a problem. I need every curved body to get you one. 

All jokes aside, body confidence— after years of speaking to yourself in dismissive, neglect and hiding it behind baggy clothes—is a practice. It takes work, but it’s worth it. 

All jokes put back in place— the third picture is an optical illusion. The dress fits well (get it), but my booty don’t be doing all that. I’m just as confused as you are. 

January was a ride, but it’s ending better than it began.  What’s up, February? 

I included the last video because that dog was giving front row at fashion week. 

#2023andB 

Also, shout out to the @itscarolyngray and @jomotomi styling.

As many of you know, I am a champion of mental wellness. Despite my best efforts, sometimes the brain and the life collide in ways that make breathing and heartbeat difficult. It happens. You give it a name. You find breath. You relocate heartbeat. You lean towards the sun— that sun can be loved ones or a higher power— until the sun starts to lean toward you. 
In my case, we change meds; we focus on health, we make necessary changes, and we name it so we can change it. 

Then we give it time. We give it time and a limit. You have permission to feel every jagged edge of life. You also have permission to feel every warm and treasured, and soft. Take the time it takes*. Gather your army. Remember that love is muscle and song. 
I promise that makes sense. 

This quote has been the affirmation for days now. I've always believed it to be true. It just takes some work to make belief strong-- like a muscle. It just takes repetition, and the sound of your body belonging to you learn it by heart-- like song. 

I told you it would make sense-- if you're into mixing metaphors.

Anyway, they call this “proof of life.”

Kiss both shoulders and the inside of each wrist. Love someone and mean it. Choose you always.

*But don’t let it go on too long

In this season of college acceptance announcements, social media is flooded with proud parents boasting about their seniors' achievements: the number of acceptance letters, scholarship money offered, and exciting plans for the future. It's truly heartwarming to witness the growth of your children over the years. I may not like every post or comment often-- if at all-- but it is a silent joy. 

But amidst the loud cheers, the glowing pride, the likes and echos of congratulations, I also hear the silent struggles of parents who are not posting. Perhaps the college application process didn't go as planned, and there were no acceptance letters or scholarships to share. Maybe there were waitlists, gap years, or unexpected turns in life that required a change of plans. Or maybe just getting through these challenging few years was an accomplishment in itself for your family. I mean, we lost three years of high school to a world-changing pandemic. These were not easy times. 

I want you to know that I see you. I recognize the effort, dedication, and love you have poured into your children, regardless of the outcome. You are doing great, and your resilience is admirable. Whether your children end up attending college or not, I hope that you can find joy and fulfillment in the journey and the destination. The summer and the rest of your life are full of possibilities, and I encourage you to explore and cherish every moment, no matter where you end up.

Because look where you came from; look how far you come--I'm so fucking proud of you.

Back in March, I had the distinct honor of participating in the @bbc documentary, “The Trouble With Kanye,” hosted by the brilliant @mobeen_azhar. The documentary is currently airing and can be found on @bbcplayer. I was also honored to be part of the accompanying podcast, “The Kanye Story”. In both, I do my best to contextualize Kanye’s behavior through the lens of bipolar disorder using my own smaller-scale lived experience. Not offering excuses but providing reasons. 

As many of you know, other than casual commentary, I’ve made it a point to avoid all media requests to speak about him. This was different. The approach was compassionate about his disorder (which he has been open about) while condemning and attempting to understand his behavior. It is a delicate balance, and this documentary did it well.

It was a pleasure to be part of the conversation, and if you can, please check out the doc on BBC Player and the podcast any and everywhere podcasts are found. 

Also, can’t tell me I’m not serving in this beach shot…

#kanyewest #thetroublewithkanye #bbc

A few months back, I uncovered a truth I'd been carrying for a decade—only to realize it was a fabricated lie intended to harm me. Someone twisted my openness about my mental health to systematically break me down and shatter my self-worth—just to protect their own fear of loss, misplaced jealousy, and perceived threat that never existed. This single act of cruelty wreaked havoc on my life and triggered experiences that nearly ended me. Since I discovered the truth, I've been grappling with patches of anxiety that have literally altered the way I breathe. I thought I wanted revenge but what I have is pity; what I need is to regain control of my story. 

I set out on a mission to heal—not to forgive just yet. My wounds are too fresh for that. Instead, I'm focused on letting go, finding my place in this vast universe, and fully embracing my identity without reservation. It's about reclaiming the truth: that the narrative imposed on me, which I naively accepted, was never my own story. This distortion warped how I saw myself and wreaked havoc on my relationship with my well-being. I fell for the lie.

But I don't buy into that lie anymore. No more people-pleasing: I won't be the one to offer an entire bakery, give out baking advice, and eagerly provide ingredients, only to receive a few crumbs as a token gesture for a wrongdoing I didn't commit. Just to get fleeting moments of release wrapped in a mix of absolution and entanglement. 

This journey goes beyond the simplistic concept of "self forgiveness" It's a complicated process, one that's crucial to grasp and then heal from. It's constant effort—work that never truly ends. But like all challenging endeavors, it's undoubtedly worth it.

What should I let go of? What lessons do I need to embrace to find a life filled with peace and fulfillment? These were the thoughts at the center of today's meditation. I hope to share more of these reflections regularly.

Gratitude to @noireboss1 for their insights and wisdom and for introducing me to @beautifulchorus. Their music has become a comforting backdrop for my thoughts, especially when my mind can't find silence.

#HealingJourney #FacingAnxiety

A few weeks ago, I had the privilege of being a guest on the "What Is a Good Life?" podcast hosted by Mark McCartney. The "What Is a Good Life" podcast is an engaging and thought-provoking podcast that explores the multifaceted concept of a fulfilling life. Episodes often touch on subjects such as philosophy, psychology, spirituality, self-improvement, and societal influences on our perceptions of what constitutes a meaningful existence. The conversations are typically characterized by deep, introspective discussions and a genuine exploration of different viewpoints.

Overall, "What Is a Good Life" aims to inspire its audience to think critically about their own paths to fulfillment and happiness, offering a platform for meaningful dialogue and self-discovery.

All that aside, outside of just being a podcast, It was also one of the best conversations I’ve ever had. 
I want to extend my gratitude to Mark for his kind, empathetic, and thought-provoking approach to some tough questions and things I’d never considered. Half the time, I wasn’t sure if I was answering the question he asked. 

All that said, it was an absolute joy and pleasure being on the show. I could have spoken to Mark for hours. 

Thank you, Mark, and congratulations on baby, Ava! 

The episode is linked in my bio.  I hope you like listening to it as much as I liked being part of it. 

Also, I don’t know why I was yelling voice all LOUD

#WhatIsAGoodLife #BasseyIkpi

A few weeks ago, while cleaning my bathroom, I went into the sink cabinet looking for a trash bag. While I was there, I discovered an old shower cap that I hadn't used or needed in years. It was perfectly fine; nothing was wrong with it. I just didn't need a shower cap. If you are aware of my hair journey, you know why. So, what did I do? I threw the shower cap away and went about my Scrubbin Bubbles. 

On Tuesday, I made a trip down to ATL to see the kind-hearted, Fairy Hair Mother @kanishiafairyhairmother . I made the pilgrimage to get another of her custom units – we don't talk about the last one (may she rest in my closet). When I got to the salon, she excitedly suggested that I keep the unit long instead of the shorter look I'm used to. I said sure! Since I cut my locs, I missed a little whip-back-and-forth moment.

The trip was just a day trip, so, after tacos with the lovely @onlychyld was back home about 12 hours later. The next morning, after thinking about the possibility of maybe working out, I grabbed my robe and headed to the bathroom. But wait! My hair is long now! I can't just hop in the shower raw. You know what I needed? A shower cap. The same one I had carelessly thrown away a few short weeks ago. I had to resort to fashioning one out of a trash bag to keep my hair from getting wet.

You know what this experience taught me? 
Nothing. Who cares? 

I just wanted to post this cute ass picture.

Thank God I don’t look like what I’ve been through.
The humidity is my filter though! Not even sunscreen on the face just lipgloss on the lips. 
America could never! 
(This is the only thing Nigeria got right for me… good for her.) 

@betterhelp do you do group therapy? And by group I mean Nigeria.

Navigating through phases of depression is a journey. Live about moving through sections of depression. We need to reframe the language around saying, “I just got out of a depressive episode,” when what you mean is, I’m not crying.” This is a process. Give yourself time and room for that process and progress. 

(PS. An hour after this photo, I was, in my hotel room, sobbing)

But we up!  On to the next stage.

There is a lot to reflect on in 2023. There were a lot of blessings and a lot of not so beautiful lessons; some  necessary and some “I could have gone my entire life not knowing any of this”. I received information that restored and then  fractured. I’ll get into all of that at a later date.  You’ll see some changes on this page again more later. 
What I will say now is this: 

I was so damn fine in 2023. I only hope I can match, maintain or multiply this level of fine moving forward. I will do my best to do so. It’s a difficult job but I’ve faced more difficult things. 

Jokes aside, I am leaving 2023 firmly behind me. All lessons learned should not have been taught in the first place. #FTSUABBMBANAHWBBWHEAUAW 

Very much looking forward to #2024. I’ll tell y’all about that later This post is purely for vanity and #FTSUABBMBANAHWBBWHEAUAW  #WeMove
